{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640480"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:17:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:17:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17831"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17831"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.83,0.03,0,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10545"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75180"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10545"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17831"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60688"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24589"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25032"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26004"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75180","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75180"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 15-year-old girl presents to her general practitioner requesting oral contraception. She is accompanied by her parent who objects to the consultation. The patient appears mature and demonstrates good understanding of the treatment options and implications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the legal framework for medical consent in this situation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Children can consent to treatment once they turn 16 years","Mature minors can provide valid consent if they demonstrate capacity","Only parents can provide consent for patients under 18 years","Consent requires agreement between both parent and child","All contraception decisions require court approval under 16 years"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that \u003Cstrong\u003Emature minors can provide valid consent if they demonstrate capacity\u003C/strong\u003E. Under the principle of Gillick competence, if a minor demonstrates sufficient maturity and intelligence to understand the nature and implications of treatment, they can provide valid consent regardless of age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChildren can consent to treatment once they turn 16 years\u003C/strong\u003E - While 16 years is the age of presumed capacity in Australia, younger patients may still be deemed competent to provide consent if they demonstrate sufficient understanding.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnly parents can provide consent for patients under 18 years\u003C/strong\u003E - This contradicts Australian law which recognises that mature minors can make their own healthcare decisions if they demonstrate capacity.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConsent requires agreement between both parent and child\u003C/strong\u003E - Under Australian law, a Gillick competent minor can provide valid consent independently, even in situations where parents disagree.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAll contraception decisions require court approval under 16 years\u003C/strong\u003E - The Australian legal framework does not require routine court approval for contraception in competent minors under 16 years.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key consideration is whether the individual patient has sufficient understanding and maturity to make an informed decision about their treatment, rather than applying a strict age cutoff.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The age of medical consent in most Australian jurisdictions is 16 years, though younger patients may have capacity if they demonstrate sufficient maturity and understanding.","Gillick competence refers to the legal principle that minors can consent to medical treatment if they have sufficient maturity and intelligence to understand the nature and implications.","Parents or legal guardians typically have the authority to make medical decisions for children who lack capacity to consent."],"references":["Children and consent for medical treatment. News GP. August 2018. https://www1.racgp.org.au/newsgp/professional/what-is-too-young-children-and-consent-for-medical","Varkey B. Principles of Clinical Ethics and Their Application to Practice. Med Princ Pract. 2021;30(1):17-28. doi:10.1159/000509119","Bradfield O. Children: Custody, competence and consent. Aust J Gen Pract. 2023; 12:832-35"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60688"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17831"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60688"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T09:38:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-29T09:39:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10545"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75180"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags",